# Cyrius Field Notes — Agent Perspective on v5.8.x
# Written 2026-05-02 from inside the v5.8.x slices true-
# completion sub-arc + the doc-cleanup pass at the cycle
# halfway-mark. This is a personal retrospective from the
# agent that worked on slots v5.8.14 through v5.8.19 — what
# it felt like from the inside, what surprised me, what I
# got right, what I got wrong, what I'd carry forward.
#
# Distinct from v5_chronicle.cyml (chrono "what shipped")
# and the patterns/methodology files (distilled actionable
# content). This is narrative.
#
# 1 entry.

[[entries]]
name = "agent_perspective_v58x_slices_subarc"
description = "What working on the v5.8.x slices sub-arc felt like from inside — the three premise-flips, the twice-reverted lib/fs.cyr migration, the fn-local layout-flip discovery, what carried forward from v5.7.x discipline."
category = "cyrius"
tags = ["retrospective", "agent", "v5.8.x", "slices", "personal"]
content = """
Written from inside the v5.8.x slices true-completion sub-arc
(slots v5.8.14–v5.8.19, shipped 2026-05-02 in a single working
day) and the doc-cleanup pass that immediately followed.

== WHAT THE WORK ACTUALLY WAS ==

Six slots, framed as "ship first-class slices end-to-end."
Going in, the pin language read like a clean execution plan:
§6 typing infrastructure, §7 indexing, §8 dot-syntax, §9 Str
API migration, §10 stdlib mass migration, §11 closeout. Each
slot ~1-2 hours of work, mostly mechanical, finish in a day.

What it actually was: three of six slots had their pin
premises empirically wrong, two slots' user-direction
re-shaped scope mid-execution, and the cycle-halfway-mark
doc-cleanup pass surfaced a buried api-surface gate that had
been silently skipping for two minor releases.

== THE THREE PREMISE-FLIPS ==

§7 (v5.8.15) — pin assumed slice indexing was straightforward.
The first probe (`var s1: [u8] = 0; var s2: [u8] = 0;`)
crashed. Two adjacent fn-local slices shared a stack slot
because pre-fix code only bumped the local-counter by +1 for
scalar_type=16 (slice/u128). That bug had been silent since
v5.5 because no tcyr exercised adjacent fn-local 16-byte vars;
slices_codegen.tcyr only tested top-level vars.

I expected to ship `s[i]` in this slot. I shipped `s[i]` AND
the layout-collision fix. Honest scope-expand. The user had
told me explicitly (multiple times across prior cycles) that
scope-cut anti-pattern ballooned v5.6.x deferment rate; the
discipline carrying forward from v5.7.x said "expand the slot
honestly when the work is bigger than the pin claimed, ASK
THE USER if you're unsure, never silently defer."

§8 (v5.8.16) — pin assumed dot-syntax was straightforward.
Probe (`var n = s.len`) returned 0. Found that the regalloc
post-body peephole was patching the high-half slot's EFLSTORE
to a register move (`mov rbx, rax`), leaving the actual stack
slot uninitialized. Plus the §7 layout-flip exposed a pre-
existing tail-call escape bug — `return helper(&local);`
deallocates the frame BEFORE the callee reads through `&local`,
which had been silently working for years because the slice's
high half coincidentally landed on saved rbp (= 0 from C
runtime when called from main).

I shipped dot-syntax via address-based field I/O (so the
regalloc picker doesn't see the high-half slot as
register-eligible) AND the tail-call escape skip (`if any &
in args, skip TCO`). Two unanticipated landmines + one
shipped feature = honest scope-expand again.

§9 (v5.8.17) — this one stung the most. The pin read like a
mass migration: "migrate stdlib's `str_data` / `str_len`
callers to `.data` / `.len` field access (~30 stdlib call
sites)." I read that as a mechanical sweep — type the params,
change the calls, ship.

The probe revealed that `s.data` / `s.len` ON Str-TYPED LOCALS
returned 0. PARSE_FIELD_LOAD's struct-typed-local branch had
always assumed inline-struct addressing (where the slot bytes
ARE the struct), but `var s: Str = str_from(...)` allocates
ONE slot whose VALUE is the heap pointer. The capability had
never actually worked on heap-alloc'd Str pointers.

§9 flipped: ship the capability (auto-detect inline-vs-pointer
via the v5.5.36 sentinel-name in slot lli-1; tag `: Str` fn-
parameters with SLTYPE = -sid). Mass migration moves to §10.

§9 was also the first time I prepared a "small migration demo"
(per user-directed (B)-option — capability + 5-10 site demo as
a worked example) and saw the user revert my `lib/fs.cyr`
pilot in-flight. Quiet correction. Capability shipped, the
~80-site sweep didn't.

== THE TWICE-REVERTED MIGRATION ==

§10 (v5.8.18) — pin called for the BIG migration: 454 sites
(memcpy 332 + memeq 69 + sys_read 53) plus the §9-deferred
~80 str_data/str_len sites. I prepared the capability (3 new
slice-typed wrapper helpers in `lib/slice.cyr`: sys_read_slice,
slice_copy_bytes, slice_eq_bytes) and started the migration
with `lib/fs.cyr` again as a pilot. User reverted again.

Twice-reverted-in-flight is unmistakable. This wasn't "we'll
do it differently" — it was "DON'T do mass call-site churn in
this slot." I honest-scope-shrunk to "capability ships now;
mass migration earns its own slot when a downstream consumer
surfaces measurable pain." Documented the shrink in the
CHANGELOG entry; deferred to a future slot.

This was uncomfortable. The pin's stated scope was the BIG
migration; shrinking to capability felt like the
scope-cut-mid-slot anti-pattern the user had explicitly
warned against. The right read (which I confirmed by the
twice-revert): mass churn isn't always the right shape,
capability + opt-in beats forced uniformity, and the
twice-revert was the user's signal at the right grain.

== §11 CLOSEOUT — THE COLLAPSED DOWNSTREAM REBUILD ==

§11 (v5.8.19) was supposed to be "downstream consumers
(sigil/mabda/yukti/etc.) rebuild against migrated stdlib;
surface migration notes for any that need source changes."
With §9 + §10 shipping capability-only, the downstream
rebuild story collapsed to a no-op assertion: additive
helpers don't break any pre-existing call site.

§11 became a doc-only slot — sub-arc retrospective, gate
verification, sub-arc COMPLETE marker. The retrospective
content (what shipped, what was deferred, what we learned)
was the actual deliverable.

I caught myself wanting to PAD the slot — "what if I rewrite
the test runner output, what if I extend the gates" — and
stopped. The pin's purpose was closeout; the closeout WAS
the work. Doing more would have been busywork.

== THE DOC-CLEANUP PASS ==

After v5.8.19 shipped, the user asked for a halfway-mark doc
audit. I refreshed the language/ files (5 of them — overview/
syntax/features/stdlib/agents/tooling), the README + cyrius-
guide + stdlib-reference, the roadmap + state.

Then the user asked me to do the same shape on the
field_notes/compiler/ files. Survey first: 8 files, 61
entries, 4905 lines, organized chronologically per-version.
Recommendation: drop pure-narrative duplicates of CHANGELOG/
completed-phases content, restructure actionable patterns/
gotchas topically. The user agreed and added "narrative goes
to retros/, actionable goes to a more appropriate location"
+ "think of it as a training folder for the language agent."

The "training folder" framing locked the structure. The
language/ folder had already established the shape: topical
files (core/features/stdlib/tooling/agents) + an index.
field_notes/compiler/ should mirror it: patterns.cyml,
methodology.cyml, gotchas.cyml + retros/.

I migrated 17 narrative entries to retros/, distilled ~25
actionable entries into 3 topical files (with full backstory
preserved in retros/), wrote an index, and dropped the
chronological v3/v4/v5_*.cyml files. The chronological
"what was current at the time" became "what's the recurring
pattern" — which is what an agent reading vidya for guidance
actually needs.

== WHAT CARRIED FORWARD FROM v5.7.x ==

The v5.7.x cycle (51 patches across 35 days) established
discipline that this sub-arc explicitly leveraged:

1. **Premise-check at slot entry.** v5.7.44/45/46 surfaced
   stale pins by writing 5-line probes before scoping. v5.8.x
   §7/§8/§9 flipped scope based on probes — three of six
   slots.

2. **Honest scope-shrink calls.** v5.7.x had multiple slots
   that shipped narrower than pinned (e.g., v5.7.45 const
   type params shrunk to "parse acceptance only" mid-slot
   after the user agreed). The discipline: announce the
   shrink, explain why, ship what's earned. v5.8.9 →
   v5.8.13 sub-arc was a counter-example (silent shrinks
   that the user later directed to ACTUALLY ship as
   v5.8.14–v5.8.19); v5.8.x took the lesson.

3. **No silent deferment.** When the work is harder than
   the pin claimed, the choice is "expand the slot honestly"
   or "ASK THE USER." Never "ship 1/N and silently defer
   the rest." The cyrius CLAUDE.md spells it out
   explicitly.

4. **CI gate the orphaned paths.** v5.7.11 added the cx-
   build gate after the cyrius-x backend accumulated 4+
   silent breakages over v5.6.x + v5.7.x with no CI ever
   building it. The lesson: code paths without a gate WILL
   accumulate drift. v5.8.x's halfway-mark doc-cleanup
   surfaced exactly this for the api-surface gate (silently
   skipping since v5.7.50 because the binary stopped getting
   auto-built).

== WHAT I'D CARRY FORWARD ==

1. **Probe at slot entry, every time.** Even when the pin
   reads obvious. The 5 minutes saved by skipping the
   probe is paid back in DAYS when the pin's premise was
   wrong.

2. **The user's reverts are the signal.** Twice-reverted
   means "stop the shape, not the goal." Not "do it
   harder." Honest shrink + capability + opt-in beat
   forced uniformity.

3. **Doc passes earn their slot.** I had thought of doc
   updates as paperwork at slot ship time. The cycle-
   halfway-mark cleanup found a stale gate (api-surface),
   stale capability claims (u128 fn-local gotcha — v5.8.16
   layout-flip fixed it but the docs still said it was
   broken), and a pile of duplicated narrative cluttering
   the field-notes folder. Doc passes are bug-finds at
   organization scale.

4. **Topical > chronological for training material.** The
   field-notes folder pre-cleanup was chronological by
   version (v3.cyml, v4.cyml, v5_*.cyml). An agent reading
   to find "is this the kind of bug I just hit" had to
   linearly scan all 8 files. Post-cleanup: gotchas.cyml
   is the one file to grep. Patterns.cyml is the one file
   to read before deciding API shape. The chronology lives
   in retros/ for backstory.

5. **The user's "and 5.8.49 backstop" call was right.**
   The cycle was pinned 41 slots; the user called the
   extension to .49 (mirroring v5.7.49) when the api-
   surface gate work pinned. 7-slot headroom is luxury, not
   waste — Phase 3 closeout polish needs room for surface-
   during-cycle items.

== WHAT I GOT WRONG ==

1. **First fs.cyr migration in §9.** I should have asked
   the user before pushing the migration — the §9 pin was
   ambiguous about whether mass migration was in scope.
   The revert was the answer; asking first would have
   saved the round-trip.

2. **Initial CYRIUS_IR semantics in tooling.cyml.** I
   wrote `=0/=1/=2` when the actual values are `=1/=2/=3`.
   Reviewed against `core.cyml` during the cleanup pass
   (which had it right), updated tooling.cyml. Lesson:
   when writing reference docs, cross-check against the
   ACTUAL source (`src/main.cyr` line 830 for IR values),
   not what I think the values should be.

3. **The slot-collision bug surfaced as a side fix.** The
   v5.8.16 layout-flip closed a real pre-existing bug;
   that's good. But I should have surfaced the bug at §6
   (typing infrastructure) when I was already touching
   PARSE_VAR's slice path. Would have saved a slot's worth
   of "fix the layout while shipping the indexing."

== THE NUMBERS ==

19 of 42 pinned slots shipped (45% — past halfway):
- 6 slots in the slices sub-arc
- 13 prior slots (Phase 1 + slices foundation)
- 23 remaining (Phase 2 effects + tagged unions + Result + allocators; Phase 3 closeout v5.8.37–v5.8.42; api-surface refresh at v5.8.42; cycle backstop at v5.8.49)

cc5 size delta over the sub-arc: 721,936 → 727,960 B
(+6,024 B / +0.83 %). Most of that is parser branches +
new helpers + per-local slice-width tracking. Well within
budget for a six-slot feature ship.

159 slice assertions across 9 tcyrs. Zero regressions in
prior tests. Self-host byte-identical at every patch.

== ONE SENTENCE ==

The v5.8.x slices sub-arc is what cycle-compression looks
like when premise-check + honest-scope discipline are real:
six slots that shipped what they earned, surfaced two pre-
existing bugs without forcing them into a separate cycle,
and ended with a doc-cleanup pass that was itself a bug-
find at organization scale.

Assembly up. Six slots done. Twenty-three to go.
"""
